LifeLink – Technical Documentation
Golden Hour Emergency Intelligence System
1️⃣ System Overview
LifeLink is an integrated accident detection and emergency coordination system designed to reduce fatalities during the Golden Hour. The system combines IoT hardware, real-time data processing, and intelligent hospital allocation to ensure rapid emergency response.
The architecture is divided into four major layers:
Sensor Layer
Processing Layer
Cloud & Intelligence Layer
Response & Coordination Layer
2️⃣ System Architecture
🔹 Sensor Layer
This layer is responsible for collecting real-world accident data.
Components:
MPU6050 Accelerometer & Gyroscope
GPS Module (NEO-6M)
Optional vehicle power monitoring
Function:
Continuously monitors acceleration across X, Y, Z axes
Detects sudden impact forces
Captures real-time location coordinates
🔹 Processing Layer
Implemented using ESP32 microcontroller.
Responsibilities:
Reads acceleration values
Calculates total impact force
Classifies severity
Triggers emergency protocol
Activates buzzer for 10-second cancellation window
Impact force is calculated using:
Total Acceleration = √(x² + y² + z²)
🔹 Cloud & Intelligence Layer
Implemented using Node.js + Express backend.
Responsibilities:
Receives accident data
Classifies final severity
Performs smart hospital allocation
Prevents duplicate case assignments
Maintains emergency state tracking
🔹 Response Layer
Frontend dashboard for hospital monitoring.
Responsibilities:
Displays accident severity
Shows live location
Allows case acceptance
Updates system availability status
3️⃣ Severity Classification Algorithm
Impact thresholds:
Minor: > 2g
Moderate: > 4g
Major: > 6g
Logic:
Continuous acceleration monitoring
If threshold exceeded → mark as potential accident
Trigger 10-second confirmation window
If not cancelled → confirm accident
Assign severity category
This ensures false positives (like potholes or braking) are reduced.
4️⃣ Smart Hospital Allocation Logic
The backend follows this allocation sequence:
Filter hospitals based on severity capability
Remove unavailable hospitals
Sort eligible hospitals by distance
Assign nearest capable hospital
Lock hospital to prevent double assignment
Fallback Strategy: If no hospital is available for that severity:
Escalate to higher-capability hospital
Trigger notification for manual override
5️⃣ Emergency Workflow
Impact detected
Severity classified
GPS coordinates captured
Data transmitted to backend
Backend assigns hospital
Dashboard displays alert
Emergency response initiated
6️⃣ Hardware–Software Integration
Hardware detects accident →
Microcontroller processes data →
Cloud backend validates & allocates →
Frontend dashboard displays emergency →
Response initiated
This integrated flow minimizes delay and improves coordination efficiency.
